        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">O’Shaughnessy’s pamphlet <hi rend="italic">Darwin confounded</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8985.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">C. O’Shaughnessy 1876</ref>) purports to be a refutation of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref>, which he refers to as ‘Darwin’s Monkey’; it is written in the form of a series of letters to ‘Rupert’, according to O’Shaughnessy family tradition the name of his cat (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8984.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">D. O’Shaughnessy 2009</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">A list of O’Shaughnessy’s published titles, including <hi rend="italic">Farm stock and crops (potato blight included)</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Errors of the solar system</hi>, was published in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8985.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">C. O’Shaughnessy 1876</ref>, p. [1]; the list is reproduced in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8989.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">D. Murphy 2009</ref>, p. 58.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD’s copy of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8985.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">C. O’Shaughnessy 1876</ref>, ‘presented by the author’ and postmarked 15 February 1876, is in DAR 132: 4.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">The deleted portion of the printed circular read: ‘Your name having been given to me as being influential amongst the higher class of farmers, I shall be happy to treat with you for the agency of my work on the prevention of disease in all kinds of’.</note>
        </div>        
            
